Introduction
This project report documents my work as part of the CSE0001 – Digital Literacy course at VIT Bhopal University. The assignment is framed around a practical scenario: I have been selected as a Student Digital Ambassador, and my responsibility is to guide my peers in navigating the digital world safely, professionally, and confidently.

Across five tasks mapped to the five course modules, I have built a Digital Literacy Portfolio that covers creating awareness content, setting up a professional digital presence, exploring coding and collaboration tools, practising professional digital communication, and understanding cybercrime. All deliverables are organised in a public GitHub repository. This report presents my work, observations, and personal reflections for each task. No prior coding background was required, and every tool used is free and browser-based. This project has genuinely helped me connect classroom concepts to real digital habits I will carry forward throughout my engineering journey.
 
Task 1 – Digital Literacy Awareness Infographic
Overview
For this task, I was required to create a single-page visual resource to help my batchmates understand what Digital Literacy means and why it matters in today's world.

Tool Used
I chose Canva (canva.com) to design my infographic. Canva is a free, browser-based graphic design tool that offers a wide range of templates, icons, and layout options — making it ideal for creating visually appealing educational content without any graphic design experience.

What My Design Shows
My infographic covers the following five topics:
•	What Digital Literacy is and why it matters for engineering students
•	Safe internet practices (avoiding phishing, using strong passwords)
•	Building a professional online presence on platforms like GitHub and LinkedIn
•	Email etiquette — the do's and don'ts of writing professional emails
•	Useful digital tools for students (Google Workspace, HackerRank, Canva)

Reflection
The most interesting part of this task was learning how to communicate technical ideas visually. I discovered that less text and more icons actually makes information easier to absorb — something I had not consciously thought about before. The part I found most challenging was keeping the layout balanced: every time I added a new section, other elements would shift and I had to reorganise the grid. Overall, this task gave me a practical introduction to design thinking, and I found myself genuinely enjoying the creative process — which connects well with my personal interest in drawing and visual art.
 
