Task 3 – Coding & Collaboration Platforms
Overview
This task had two parts: exploring a coding practice platform and building a collaborative digital resource using Google Workspace tools.

Part A – Coding Practice: HackerRank
I created an account on HackerRank (hackerrank.com) and completed the 'Solve Me First' beginner challenge — a straightforward problem that asks you to read two integers and print their sum. While the logic was simple, the experience of submitting code in an online judge environment, reading the problem statement carefully, and verifying my output against test cases was genuinely new and useful. HackerRank also showed me its skill tracks in Python, SQL, and Problem Solving — all of which I plan to work through systematically. I have basic Python knowledge from school and this task gave me the confidence to build on it further.

Part B – Google Form: Digital Literacy Awareness Quiz
I created a five-question Digital Literacy Awareness Quiz using Google Forms. The quiz is designed for first-year students and includes:
•	One multiple choice question on identifying phishing emails
•	One short answer question asking students to name two digital tools they use daily
•	One multiple choice question on email etiquette
•	One true/false question on UPI safety
•	One short answer question on what students would do if they received a suspicious link

The form is linked to a Google Sheet that automatically collects and organises responses — a feature I found remarkably efficient for data collection. I have added a screenshot of both the form and the response sheet to the task-3-platforms/ folder.

Reflection
This task showed me how powerful free tools can be when used thoughtfully. HackerRank gave me a structured way to practise coding with immediate feedback, while Google Forms demonstrated how collaboration tools can be used not just for surveys but for real academic purposes like quizzes and data collection. Both platforms will be part of my academic toolkit going forward.
 
Task 4 – Professional Email & Etiquette Guide
Overview
This task focused on professional digital communication — one of the most underrated yet critical skills for students entering university life and eventually the workforce.

Emails Drafted
I drafted two professional emails (both saved in task-4-email-etiquette/):
•	Email 1 to a professor requesting a three-day extension on the CSE0001 project submission. I was careful to open with a respectful greeting, state the reason clearly and briefly, make a specific and reasonable request, and close with gratitude and a professional sign-off.
•	Email 2 to an internship coordinator expressing interest in a summer internship. This email required a slightly different tone — confident but not overreaching — and needed to briefly highlight my skills (Python, HTML, frontend interest) while linking to my GitHub portfolio.

Social Media Checklist
I also created a Social Media Do's and Don'ts checklist (saved as social-media-checklist.md) with seven points in each category. Key do's include keeping profiles professional, sharing your learning publicly, and engaging respectfully. Key don'ts include posting personal information, venting about academic issues online, and clicking unverified links from DMs.

Communication Scenario & Reflection
A situation that illustrates the cost of poor digital communication: In 2017, a medical student in India lost a job offer after a recruiter discovered that their social media profile contained posts making fun of their college exams and professors. The posts were years old but still publicly visible. What could have been done differently? The student could have regularly reviewed their privacy settings, set older posts to 'friends only', and thought about long-term audience before posting. This example taught me that everything we post online creates a permanent record — and that record can have real professional consequences even years later. I will personally audit my own social media profiles as a result of this task.
 
Task 5 – Cybercrime Awareness: Phishing
Overview
This task required me to research a cybercrime type, write a detailed case study, and build a prevention checklist targeted at college students in India.

Cybercrime Type: Phishing
I chose phishing because it is the most widespread and frequently evolving cybercrime, and one that college students encounter almost immediately — through fake exam portal emails, scholarship fraud messages, and impersonation attacks on social media.

Case Study Summary
My case study (casestudy.md) describes a realistic scenario in which a first-year student named Riya receives an email that appears to come from her university's exam portal. The email warns her that her semester registration will be cancelled unless she verifies her credentials within 24 hours — a classic urgency-based phishing trigger. The fake website she is directed to captures her login credentials, which the attacker then uses on the real portal. The case study explains the five-step attack process, who is typically targeted, and the academic and personal consequences.

Prevention Checklist
My prevention-checklist.md includes ten actionable tips, including two specific to UPI/financial safety: never scan QR codes sent by strangers for 'receiving' money, and always set a daily UPI transaction limit. The checklist also includes official reporting channels: cybercrime.gov.in and Helpline 1930.

Reflection
What surprised me most while researching phishing was how convincing modern phishing emails have become — many of them now pass basic grammar and visual checks. I had always assumed that spelling errors were a reliable red flag, but that is no longer always true. The habit I will personally change is to always verify the actual URL of any website before entering my credentials, rather than trusting how the page looks. I will also enable Two-Factor Authentication on every account that supports it — something I had been putting off until now.
 
Conclusion
Completing this Digital Literacy Portfolio has been one of the most practically useful assignments I have encountered in my first year of engineering. Unlike traditional examinations, this project required me to actually use the tools, platforms, and skills being assessed — which made the learning concrete and memorable.

I now have a GitHub repository, a LinkedIn profile, a Kaggle account, experience with HackerRank, a published Google Form, and a clear understanding of phishing and online safety. More importantly, I have begun to think of my digital footprint as something I am actively building and responsible for — not just a passive by-product of being online. I look forward to continuing to grow this portfolio throughout my four years at VIT Bhopal University.

